04045nam a22005655i 9780822395126DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20142014ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223951267 a10.1515/97808223951262doi  a(DE-B1597)554613  a(OCoLC)873034791  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDC33.7b.S27 2014eb 7aLIT0041502bisacsh04a840.9/35840532231 aSapiro, Gisèle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe French Writers' War, 1940-1953 /cGisèle Sapiro. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (752 p.) :b5 tables, 4 graphs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics, History, and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART I The Literary Logics of Political Engagement -- t1 Choices under Constraints -- t2 The Responsibility of the Writer -- t3 Literary Salvation and the Literature of Salvation -- tPART II Literary Institutions and National Crisis -- t4 The Sense of Duty -- t5 The Sense of Scandal -- t6 The Sense of Distinction -- t7 The Sense of Subversion -- tPART III Literary Justice -- t8 The Literary Court -- t9 Literary Institutions and National Reconstruction -- tConclusion -- tAppendix 1: Presentation of the Survey -- tAppendix 2: The Social Recruitment of the Literary Field and of Its Institutions -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tName Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe French Writers' War, 1940-1953, is a remarkably thorough account of French writers and literary institutions from the beginning of the German Occupation through France's passage of amnesty laws in the early 1950s. To understand how the Occupation affected French literary production as a whole, Gisèle Sapiro uses Pierre Bourdieu's notion of the "literary field." Sapiro surveyed the career trajectories and literary and political positions of 185 writers. She found that writers' stances in relation to the Vichy regime are best explained in terms of institutional and structural factors, rather than ideology. Examining four major French literary institutions, from the conservative French Academy to the Comité national des écrivains, a group formed in 1941 to resist the Occupation, she chronicles the institutions' histories before turning to the ways that they influenced writers' political positions. Sapiro shows how significant institutions and individuals within France's literary field exacerbated their loss of independence or found ways of resisting during the war and Occupation, as well as how they were perceived after Liberation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aIntellectualszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh1 aCohn, Dorrit1 aDoriott Anderson, Vanessa08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395126zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395126423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395126.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles